# Best Practices

## TypeScript

- Use TypeScript strict mode
- Don't use `any` type, use `unknown` if needed
- Use proper types for all variables and functions
- Use interfaces and types appropriately

## Code Style

- Use async/await instead of Promises.then()
- Handle errors through try-catch or exceptions
- Use transactions for complex operations
- Use dependency injection instead of creating instances manually

## Constants & Configuration

- Don't hardcode values, use constants or configuration
- Use enum for statuses and roles
- Store configuration in environment variables
- Use @nestjs/config for configuration management

## Code Organization

- Follow DRY principle (Don't Repeat Yourself)
- Extract reusable logic into services or utilities
- Keep functions small and focused
- Use meaningful variable and function names

## Documentation

- Add JSDoc comments for complex methods
- Comment non-obvious business logic
- Document API endpoints with Swagger
- Keep README updated

## Git & Commits

- Use conventional commits:
  - `feat:` - New feature
  - `fix:` - Bug fix
  - `test:` - Adding tests
  - `refactor:` - Code refactoring
  - `docs:` - Documentation
  - `chore:` - Maintenance tasks

- Commit frequently, in small chunks
- Don't commit: node_modules, .env, dist/

## Performance

- Use database indexes for frequently queried fields
- Optimize database queries (avoid N+1 problems)
- Use pagination for large datasets
- Cache frequently accessed data when appropriate

## Security

- Never expose sensitive data in responses
- Hash passwords using bcrypt
- Validate all input data
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Implement rate limiting for API endpoints

## When Creating New Functionality

1. Create entity (if needed)
2. Create database migration
3. Create DTOs for validation
4. Create service with business logic
5. Create controller with endpoints
6. Add module to AppModule
7. Write tests (unit + e2e)
8. Add Swagger documentation
9. Check validation and error handling
